Figure 5
 shows the IFE-based fluorescence spectra of NCPDs in the presence of pesticides. The excitation spectrum of NCPDs completely matches the absorption band pesticide DCR (350 nm), and the emission is partially overlapped in the case of p-NP. Because of these overlaps, the NCPDs emission can be partially absorbed by the analytes (a phenomenon based on the inner filter effect mechanism) or can be quenched by a non-radiative energy transfer process by the FRET mechanism [11] (see discussion after Fig. 6
). Both processes decrease the NCPDs emission intensities.
